 where, CIL is valuable thing index long positions and CIS is valuable thing index short positions. 
 Changes in the PNL for valuable thing index money is used to take by force/take control of moves/changes in their positions within 
 each market. These two measures--percent of long positions and change in the PNL--are used to 
 test for the possible result of index traders across markets. 
 Cross-Sectional Tests 
 Fama-MacBeth Cross-Sectional (moving backwards) 
 
 The relationship between index fund positions and later market returns can be expressed in a 
 thin sliceal moving backward, 
 (2) 
 
 Ri,t+1= Î± + Î²Positionsi,t + ei,t 
 
 The null guess of no market hit/effect is that the slope coefficient,Î², equals zero. An different 
 bubble guess would suggest that Î²&amp;gt;0, such that large index fund positions in market i predict 
 (compared to other things) large later returns in that market. In all (moving backwards), the data are organized such 
 that the (proof that one thing definitely causes another) linkages run from the positions at time t to the later returns in time t+1. 
 Therefore, a finding that Î²a 0 hints that index positions happen before market returns. 
 Fama and MacBeth (1973) propose one method of guessing Î² in (2) that is still widely used in the 
 books (see Campbell, Lo, and MacKinley 1997). With the Fama-MacBeth moving backward procedure, 
 equation (2) is guessed independently for each time period, t=1,2,3,...T, and across the 
 i=1,2,3,...,N markets. The average of the guessed Î²'s is calculated for the T (moving backwards), and it 
 has a standard error of 1/T1/2. To illustrate, Figure 4 shows one of the T (moving backwards) at the quarterly 
 (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet). In this particular quarter (t=third quarter, 2008), markets that had a (compared to other things) large portion 
 of long positions held by index traders in fact saw (compared to other things) stronger returns in the later 
 period, agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with a bubble-like hit/effect across markets. Other (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements), such as shown in 
 Figure 5 (t=second quarter, 2007), show a negative relationship between index fund positions and 
 returns. The Fama-MacBeth procedure mostly averages the thin sliceal slope coefficient 
 across all of the time series (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) and tests if the average is different from zero. The FamaMacbeth procedure is managed and did/done for weekly, monthly, and quarterly horizons resulting in 156, 35, 
 an 11 thin sliceal (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements), (match up each pair of items in order). 
 The Fama-MacBeth results are presented in Table 1 for equation (2), where positions are 
 represented by the percent of long positions held by index traders. Somewhat surprisingly, the 
 average slope coefficient at each (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet)  is negative; although, not (related to numbers) different from zero. 
 These results would suggest that if anything, markets with (compared to other things) large index trader positions 
 tend to have (compared to other things) smaller price increases in later time periods. 
 Table 2 presents the results for the Fama-MacBeth (moving backwards) where the (thing that you control (like study time), that causes something else to change (like a test score)) is the 
 change in index fund's PNL position. Here, the results are just like those in Table 1 at the 
 monthly and quarterly (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet), where the slope coefficients are negative and not (related to numbers) 
 different from zero. A (a) little different result is watched/followed at the weekly (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet), where the slope 
 coefficient is positive. But, it is still not (related to numbers) different from zero. Together, the Fama- 
 
