 MacBeth (moving backwards) provide no (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that index positions cause differential returns across 
 valuable thing futures markets. 
 Cross-Sectional Time Series (moving backwards) 
 
 Standard cross sectional time series methods are another approach to guessing equation (2). 
 However, this method provides greater flexibility than the Fama-MacBeth approach in terms of 
 model (detailed description of exactly what is required) because time series patterns can also be modeled. Sanders, Irwin, and Merrin 
 (2009) document some low-order positive autocorrelation in valuable thing futures returns. Consistent 
 with that finding, we specify the following model. 
 (3) 
 
 Ri,t+1= Î± + Î²Positionsi,t +Î¸Rt + ei,t 
 
 Where returns in market i at time t+1 are a function of index fund positions and returns from the 
 previous period. White's correction for thin sliceal heteroskedasticity is used to get 
 consistent standard errors in (3). 
 Table 3 presents the cross sectional time series guesses using index money' percent of long 
 positions as the (thing that you control (like study time), that causes something else to change (like a test score)). The results are very agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the Fama-MacBeth 
 moving backward results in Table 1. The guessed slope coefficients are negative at each (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet), but they 
 are not (related to numbers) different from zero. So, again, there is no (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that the cross-market 
 difference/different version in returns is related to long-only index fund positions. Famously, the returns do tend to 
 show some low order positive autocorrelation, Î¸&amp;gt;0. 
 Equation (3) is also guessed with the change in the index fund's PNL as the explanatory (number or thing that changes) 
 (Table 4). At the monthly and quarterly horizons, the guessed beta coefficients are still negative 
 and not (related to numbers) different from zero. However, as in Table 2, the one week (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet)  has a 
 positive and (only a little bit) significant guessed beta coefficient (p-value =0.06). So, there is some 
 very modest (number-based information that proves something) that the weekly thin sliceal returns may be positively related to 
 the previous/coming before week's change in the index fund positions. The results are only (only a little bit) 
 significant, so they do not provide (very big/very strong) (number-based information that proves something). But, they do raise the 
 possibility that hits/effects may be found over some shorter horizons or with different position 
 measures. 
 Together, the scientific results generally do not reject the null guess that there is no crossmarket relationship between returns and the size of index fund positions. The alone  exception is a 
 not important rejection (p-value = 0.06) at the one week (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet)  using the move/change in the PNL as the 
 explanatory (number or thing that changes). Otherwise, the relationship between cross market index positions and returns 
 tends to be negative instead of positive. It is hard to (cause agreement with) these results with the 
 statement that index fund buying is new demand in each market. 
 Summary and Ends/end results 
 
 This research examines the cross-market relationship between market returns and positions held by 
 long-only index money. Irwin, Sanders, and Merrin (2009) state that one of the "(not agreeing/not happening in the same way) facts" 
 
 7 
 
 in the bubble explanation for the recent increase and decline in valuable thing markets is that the price 
 increases (decreases) did not happen completely across all markets. That is, if index money drove 
 prices higher, then they should have had an hit/effect in all of the markets, not just select ones. 
 Here, we provide an scientific test of this (not agreeing/not happening in the same way) fact. Specifically, we test if the relative size 
 of index fund positions is related to later returns across markets. A bubble picture/situation would 
 suggest that returns are positively related to relative positions sizes across markets. However, 
 using both Fama-MacBeth and traditional cross sectional tests, the null guess of no crosssectional hit/effect is only rejected in one of twelve models. 
 The (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that index fund positions hit/effect returns across markets is very little. This leaves a big 
 hole in the bubble argument. If index fund buying represents new demand that drives prices higher, 
 then why doesn't the new demand have an hit/effect in each market? Like all explanations, the bubble 
 explanation claimed in the popular press should be tested based on its ability to (describe the future). In the case 
 of (describing the future) cross sectional returns, the explanation falls short. 
 Statements that money-makers drive prices beyond basic value and disrupt important 
 people-helping efforts have been the spark for recent law-based proposals designed to control 
 guess/guessing in valuable thing futures markets. Given the importance of money-makers in a well 
 functioning (place where people buy things) it is important the policy-makers think about/believe the whole body of (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) with 
 regard to the hit/effect of money-makers on market prices. 
 Almost all evidence presented by school-related (people who work to find information) does not find any 
 relationship between positions held by large traders and later price behavior (e.g., Bryant, 
 Bessler, and Haigh 2006; Gorton, Hayashi, and Rouwenhorst 2007; Sanders, Irwin, and Merrin 
 2009). Those that do find some (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) (e.g., Robles, Torero, and Braun 2009) often use nonstandard ways of doing things or data (e.g., cash or index prices). Therefore, even though the arguments made 
 by bubble supporters are obviously appealing to the non-money-flow expert, they do not stand on a firm 
 scientific footing. While difficult/strict/high quality scientific studies cannot prevent a based on guessing/guessed hit/effect on 
 valuable thing prices, the body of (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) certainly does not support that end/end result. Law-makers and 
 public policy talkers would be well-served to let this (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) guide their actions. 
 
